Title : Henry Carden
Text : {{Portal|Anglicanism}}[[The Venerable|The Ven]] '''Henry Craven Carden''' (23 December 1882<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p20264.htm#i202632 thePeerage.com]</ref> &ndash; 30 October 1964<ref>''Deaths.'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Monday, Nov 02, 1964; pg. 1; Issue 56158</ref>) was [[Archdeacon]] of [[Lahore]] from 1929 to<ref>'' Points from Letters'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Monday, May 30, 1932; pg. 8; Issue 46146</ref> 1934.

Born into an [[Carden baronets|aristocratic family]], he was educated at [[Hatfield College, Durham]] and [[ordained]] in 1907.<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]] 1947-48 p202: Oxford, [[Oxford University Press|OUP]], 1947</ref>  He was  [[Curate]] at St Peter with St Owen, [[Hereford]]<ref>[http://www.achurchnearyou.com/hereford-st-peter-st-owen/ Church details]</ref> then St Mary, [[Ross-on-Wye]].<ref>[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2751865 Geograph]</ref> He was [[Chaplain]] at [[Cathedral Church of the Resurrection, Lahore|Lahore Cathedral]] until [[World War One|war]] broke out when he became a [[Chaplain]] with the [[Mesopotamian Expeditionary Force]]. When peace returned he served the [[Anglican Church|church]] in the [[North Western Frontier Province]] at [[Peshawar]], [[Abbottabad]] and [[Hazara District|Hazara]] before his appointment as [[Archdeacon]]; and at [[Kilmeston]] in [[Hampshire]] afterwards.

